From cou.: 4 In most cases of ordered nanoparticle assembly, a control over the interparticle distance was neither possible nor intended. For conventional nanoparticle assemblies, some control of the interparticle distance is possible via the choice of the stabilizing surfactants that can differ in the length of their alkyl chains.5 A breakthrough has been the use of DNA-ligands by Alivisatos and Mirkin et al.,6–8 who for gold nanoparticles tailored the superlattice type and nanoparticle distance via hybridization of DNA-chains. If the DNA-chains were not hybridizing, lyotropic phases of cubic symmetry were formed. The lyotropic phase behaviour could be followed by microfocus synchrotron X-ray scattering of a small droplet of a DNA-coated gold nanoparticle aqueous solution upon drying.9,10
From Soup: 4 In most cases of ordered nanoparticle assembly , a control over the interparticle distance was neither possible nor intended. For conventional nanoparticle assemblies, some control of the interparticle distance is possible via the choice of the stabilizing surfactants that can differ in the length of their alkyl chains. 5 A breakthrough has been the use of DNA- ligands by Alivisatos and Mirkin et al. , 6–8 who for gold nanoparticles tailored the superlattice type and nanoparticle distance via hybridization of DNA-chains. If the DNA-chains were not hybridizing, lyotropic phases of cubic symmetry were formed. The lyotropic phase behaviour could be followed by microfocus synchrotron X-ray scattering of a small droplet of a DNA-coated gold nanoparticle aqueous solution upon drying. 9,10
